Oil Volatility Falls as Futures Tumble, Ending Two-Day Rally

-- B y   M a r g o t   H a b i b y
-- 
2011-07-14T20:51:22Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-14/oil-volatility-falls-as-futures-tumble-ending-two-day-rally.html
Oil options volatility slipped as
August futures snapped a two-day rally after Federal Reserve
Chairman  Ben S. Bernanke  said the central bank isnâ€™t planning
more bond-buying to stimulate economic growth.  Implied volatility for at-the-money options expiring in
September, a measure of expected price swings in futures and a
gauge of options prices, was 29.6 percent at 4 p.m. in  New York ,
down from 30.3 percent yesterday. August options expire tomorrow
at the close of New York Mercantile Exchange floor trading.  Crude for August delivery tumbled $2.36, or 2.4 percent, to
settle at $95.69 a barrel on the exchange. Prices have risen 24
percent in the past year. September futures fell $2.38, or 2.4
percent, to $96.11 a barrel.  The most active contracts in electronic trading today were
August $95 puts, with 4,236 lots changing hands. They rose 7
cents to 35 cents a barrel. August $93 puts, the next-most
active option, fell 1 cent to 10 cents a barrel with 2,155 lots
trading. One contract covers 1,000 barrels of crude.  The exchange distributes real-time data for electronic
trading and releases information on floor trading, where the
bulk of options trading occurs, the next business day.  August $93 puts were the most active options traded
yesterday, with 6,223 lots changing hands. They dropped 10 cents
to 11 cents a barrel. The next-most active options, August $100
calls, slipped 1 cent to 39 cents a barrel on volume of 5,960.  Open interest was highest for December $120 calls with
43,182 contracts. Next were December $125 calls with 41,176 and
December $100 calls with 40,454.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Margot Habiby in  Dallas  at 
 mhabiby@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Dan Stets at   dstets@bloomberg.net . 